properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall, blowing snow and strong winds expected. Total snowfall: 15 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 80 to 100 km/h. Locations: the west coast of Newfoundland. Time span: Tuesday morning to Wednesday afternoon or evening. Remarks: Snow will develop by Tuesday morning and is expected to become heavy at times Tuesday afternoon. As temperatures fall below freezing Tuesday evening, snow will combine with strong winds to reduce visibility in blowing snow. Occasional to frequent whiteout conditions are likely, especially over exposed areas where blowing snow will be more intense. strongest wind gusts will occur over the Port au Port Peninsula and south to Channel-Port aux Basques. Winds will begin to weaken on Wednesday morning. Conditions will begin to improve for some areas on Wednesday afternoon as snow changes to flurries, which will eventually taper off overnight on Wednesday night. Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Warning of potential breaking sea conditions and overwash issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec Region on 2020-12-14. Higher than normal water levels and large waves are expected near the coast during the period in question. An intense low pressure system from the US Eastern Seaboard will cause strong to severe winds over the regions listed below. Rimouski - Mont-Joli: 2020-12-15, from 12:30 PM to 04:00 PM. Matane: 2020-12-15, from 12:30 PM to 04:00 PM. Sainte-Anne-des-Monts - Grande-Vall√©e: 2020-12-15, from 12:00 PM to 03:30 PM. ### Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. With temperatures near minus 40, wind chill values will be near minus 50 at times tonight and Tuesday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 30 cm is expected. An prolonged period of snowfall is expected beginning Tuesday morning. Locations: Cartwright to Lodge Bay. Total snowfall: up to 30 cm by Wednesday morning, with potentially more amounts during the day Wednesday and Wednesday night. Time span: Wednesday morning until Thursday morning. Remarks: highest accumulations are expected over inland areas. Temperatures will be around the freezing mark along the coast, which could cause some melting to occur, resulting in reduced accumulations. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. An intense frontal system will approach the BC Coast tonight. Ahead of the front, southeast winds of 80 to 100 km/h will develop over Haida Gwaii, Central Coast - coastal sections, and North Vancouver Island this evening. These strong winds will ease before Tuesday morning as the frontal system passes. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for this afternoon and this evening. Snowfall in the 8 to 15 cm range, low visibility due to heavy falling snow and blowing snow are expected. Snow accumulating rapidly on roadways could make travel difficult during the afternoon and evening hours. Conditions should improve by midnight. This Winter Weather Travel Advisory is due to lake effect snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum wind gusts: westerly near 100 km/h. Locations: The Burin and Connaigre peninsulas. Time span: beginning Tuesday evening and lasting until Wednesday morning. Remarks: The strongest winds will occur over southern areas of both peninsulas, especially over areas exposed to the west. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
